critique: This executive order terminates certain prohibitions related to the Development Fund for Iraq, responding to changed circumstances in Iraq. It does not directly address immigration, civil liberties, or social inclusion. It grants authority to the Secretary of the Treasury, but this seems related to managing assets rather than expanding executive power in general. The order does not appear to have a strong ideological tilt. It seems to be more of an administrative action related to foreign policy and economic issues. It is difficult to assess the impact on federalism or economic regulation without more context, but it seems to be primarily focused on international economic policy.
